Checking for the Normality of the Residuals (or error)

#normality of the residuals from a linear regression model
qqnorm(residuals(model))
qqline(residuals(model),col='red')

ks.test(residuals(model),"pnorm")

Note:- Normally Distributed Residuals: The assumption is that the residuals follow a normal distribution. This assumption is important because it helps to ensure that the estimates of the regression coefficients (slope and intercept) are unbiased and efficient, and it’s a key assumption for conducting hypothesis tests and constructing confidence intervals.

use of the Analysis of Variance (ANOVA)

  • ANOVA testing whether the more complex model is significantly better at capturing the data than the simpler model.

#Simple linear regression using the lm() function

#model 1:  (only horsepower)
model1 =lm(price~horsepower,data=autos) 
# # Model 2:  (horsepower AND length)
model2  = lm(price~horsepower+length,data=autos) 

# Model 3:  (horsepower AND length AND bore)
model3  = lm(price~horsepower+length+bore,data=autos)
  • compare the two simplest models: model 1 with model 2.this ANVOA will test whether or not including the length leads to a significant improvement over using just the horsepower.
# Compare model 1 to model 2
anova(model1, model2)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Model 1: price ~ horsepower
## Model 2: price ~ horsepower + length
##   Res.Df        RSS Df Sum of Sq      F  Pr(>F)    
## 1    191 4270475650                                
## 2    190 3364697360  1 905778290 51.148 1.8e-11 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

As you can see, the result shows a Df of 1 (indicating that the more complex model has one additional parameter), and a very small p-value (< .001). This means that adding the length to the model did lead to a significantly improved fit over the model 1.

# Compare model 2 to model 3
anova(model2, model3)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Model 1: price ~ horsepower + length
## Model 2: price ~ horsepower + length + bore
##   Res.Df        RSS Df Sum of Sq      F Pr(>F)
## 1    190 3364697360                           
## 2    189 3363084277  1   1613083 0.0907 0.7637

The result shows a non-significant result (p = 0.7637). Thus, we should reject model 3 and stick with model 2 .

Checking for the Collinearity

  • Variance Inflation Factor (VIF): The VIF quantifies the extent of collinearity. You can use the vif() function from the car package to calculate VIF values for each variable. A VIF value greater than 10 is often considered a sign of problematic collinearity.
library(car)

# Calculate VIF for a linear model
model <- lm(price ~ length + engine.size + horsepower + city.mpg+bore+stroke+compression.ratio+peak.rpm, data = autos)
vif_values <- vif(model)
vif_values

#Nonparametric Regression Models

Locally Weighted Regression

-Locally Weighted Regression (often abbreviated as Loess) is a non-parametric regression method that fits a smooth curve through data points.

-The curve is flexible and adapts to the data by giving more weight to nearby data points and less weight to more distant points.

-In R, ywe can perform Loess regression using the loess() function. Here’s how to do it:

# Fit a loess regression model
loess_model <- loess(city.mpg ~ horsepower,data=autos)
loess_model
## Call:
## loess(formula = city.mpg ~ horsepower, data = autos)
## 
## Number of Observations: 193 
## Equivalent Number of Parameters: 5.37 
## Residual Standard Error: 2.673
# Generate a sequence of horsepower values
series = seq(48, 261,by=1) 
# Predict city.mpg using the loess model
predictions_loess <- predict(loess_model, data.frame(horsepower = series))

# Create a scatterplot of the data
plot(autos$horsepower, autos$city.mpg, xlab = "Horsepower", ylab = "City MPG", pch = 19, col = "blue", main = "Loess Regression")

# Add the Loess regression curve to the plot
lines(series, predictions_loess, col = "red", lwd = 2)

Comparison the log-linear regression model and loess model

# Fit a loess regression model
loessReg = loess(city.mpg ~ horsepower,data=autos) 
# Fit a linear regression model with a log-transformed predictor
logReg = lm(city.mpg ~ log(horsepower),data=autos) 
# Generate a sequence of horsepower values
series = seq(48, 261,by=1) 
# Predict city.mpg using the loess model
predictions_loess <- predict(loessReg, data.frame(horsepower = series))
# Predict city.mpg using the linear model with a log-transformed predictor
predictions_logReg <- predict(logReg, data.frame(horsepower = series))
# Create a plot
plot(series,predictions_loess , col='blue', type ='l', lty=1, xlab="horsepower", ylab = "City MPG", pch = 19,main = "Comparison of loessReg and logReg") 
points(autos$horsepower,autos$city.mpg) 
lines(series,predictions_logReg , col='red', lty=2)
legend(170, 40,  legend = c("loessReg", "logReg"), col=c('blue', 'red'), lty=1:2)

Change the span parameter

loessReg1 = loess(city.mpg ~ horsepower, span=0.21,data=autos)

Decision tree -Decision tree is a type of supervised learning algorithm that can be used in both regression and classification problems. It works for both categorical and continuous input and output variables.

-If the response variable is continuous then we can build regression trees and if the response variable is categorical then we can build classification trees.

Regression tree

#Step 1: splitting data into a training set and a testing set.

selected <- sample(1:dim(credit)[1], size=round(dim(credit)[1]*0.7))  #splitting the data into Train and test dataset
round(dim(credit)[1]*0.7)
## [1] 280
train <- credit[selected,]   # 70% t which means Randomly select 280 observations for Traning set 
test <- credit[-selected,]   # 30% which means Randomly select 120 observations for Traning set

#Step 2: Load the necessary packages.

# Install packages "rpart", "rpart.plot" first, then load them into R
#install.packages('rpart')
library(rpart)
#install.packages('rpart.plot')
library(rpart.plot)

#Step 3: Build the initial regression tree. -First, we’ll build a large initial regression tree. We can ensure that the tree is large by using a small value for cp,

# Grow regression trees
# arguments:
# cp: complexity parameter is the tuning parameter in CART.
#Any split that does not decrease the overall lack of fit by 
# a factor of cp is not attempted. 
# Used to choose depth of the tree, we'll manually prune the tree later and 
# hence can set the threshold very low.
# method: "anova" for regression tree, "class" for classification tree

#Fitting the model
fittree <- rpart(Income~., data=train, method="anova", cp=10^(-5)) 
prp(fittree, faclen=-3, extra=1, cex=.8, main="Regression Tree without Prune")

# Display the CP table
printcp(fittree)

Note:-Selecting the value of the complexity parameter (CP) is an important step in building a decision tree model. The optimal value of the CP determines the size and complexity of the tree, and can affect the model’s performance on the testing data.

-select the optimal CP value is to identify the CP value that results in the smallest cross-validation error rate (xerror)

#Step 4: Prune the tree using the best cp (i.e., the cp with the smallest cross-validation error (xerror))

#identify best cp value to use
bestcp <- fittree$cptable[which.min(fittree$cptable[,"xerror"]),"CP"]
fittreebest <- prune(fittree, cp=bestcp)
# Plot tree using package rpart.plot
prp(fittreebest, faclen=-3, extra=1, cex=.8, main="CART- best cp")

Random Forest For regression trees

-Random Forest approach is a supervised learning algorithm. It builds the multiple decision trees which are known as forest and glue them together to urge a more accurate and stable prediction.

#install.packages('randomForest')
library(randomForest)
## randomForest 4.7-1.1
## Type rfNews() to see new features/changes/bug fixes.
## 
## Attaching package: 'randomForest'
## The following object is masked from 'package:ggplot2':

##     margin

## 
##     outlier
# Do random forests
#  arguments:
#   Instead of specifying method="anova" as with rpart, 
#   if the response is a factor, classification is assumed,
#   otherwise regression is assumed.
#   importance=TRUE argument allows us to inspect variable importance 
#   ntree: number of bootstrap trees to grow
#   mtry: number of variables randomly sampled as candidates at each split. 
#         Note that the default values are different for classification (sqrt(p)) and 
#         regression (p/3)
fittreer <- randomForest(Income~., data=train, importance=T, ntree=2000, mtry=4)
print(fittreer)
## 
## Call:

# Look at what variables were important
varImpPlot(fittreer, cex=.8) #Variables with higher importance values are considered more important in predicting the response variable.

#Advantages of Random Forest:

-Efficient: Random forests are much more efficient than decision trees while performing on large databases.

-Highly accurate: Random forests are highly accurate as they are collection of decision trees and each decision tree draws sample random data and in result, random forests produces higher accuracy on prediction.

-Efficient estimates of the test error: It makes efficient use of all predictive features and maintains accuracy even if the data is missing.

#Disadvantages of Random Forest:-

-Requires different number of levels:

-Requires a lot of memory:
